    "narrative": "Our strongest play today is **Tyler Freeman** (71.80), who benefits from a dream matchup against Matt Waldron. With an opposing xERA of 7.83, **Tyler Freeman** is positioned to capitalize on a high-run environment, further buoyed by a +14% park factor and +19% SP skill adjustment. Joining him as a priority start is **Geraldo Perdomo** (65.92); despite facing a right-handed arm, his role in the #3 spot and a favorable SP xERA of 4.68 make him a core contributor. **Gavin Sheets** (63.36) also enters the strong territory, as the combination of a high-ceiling park and a +15% SP skill boost against Ryan Feltner allows him to overcome standard platoon hurdles.\n\nThe optimizer\u2019s toughest decision centered on **Matt Chapman** (57.18), who remains in the lineup despite a challenging date with Tyler Glasnow. While the elite pitcher suppresses the score, **Matt Chapman** retains value due to the \"Slow SP Delivery\" factor\u2014Glasnow\u2019s methodical pace provides a specific window for **Matt Chapman** to capitalize on potential stolen base opportunities, a critical variable given our scarcity mandate. Close behind was **Jung Hoo Lee** (51.45), whose utility rests heavily on that same stolen base potential; he edges out **Wenceel Perez** (45.20) because the latter suffers from a negative platoon adjustment and a less favorable #8 batting position. **Bryson Stott** (49.59) sits at the low end of the recommended tier; while the wind provides a +5% boost, the matchup against Matthew Boyd is tempered by his \"Elite Hold SP\" rate, which complicates his path to reaching our speed-heavy category goals.\n\nRisk remains elevated across the board as the majority of our lineup is currently marked \"Lineup Pending.\" While we have projected positions for **Will Smith**, **Luis Arraez**, and **Drew Gilbert**, we must remain vigilant for mid-day scratch updates. **Will Smith** is notably at risk; his score of 46.49 is dragged down by the efficiency of Logan Webb,